 ## About This Repository
 
-The purpose of this repository is to publish the source code for Cardinal's
-self-hosted applications for users to inspect.
-
-This is not the repository where work actively happens. This repository is a
-read-only clone of Cardinal's main (private) monorepo, but with only the
-self-hosted packages included.
-
 <details>
   <summary>How do I use this repository as someone that wants to build an app that uses Cardinal's APIs?</summary>
-  <ol>
-    <li>Consult the <a href="https://help.cardinalapps.io/guides/developers">Developer Guide</a> on the the Help Site.</li>
-    <li>Install the <strong>beta</strong> Media Server from Docker Hub and develop your app against that API. You probably don't actually need to use this repository.</li>
-    <li>You can use this repository if you want to develop against <code>latest</code> instead of <code>beta</code>. Just follow the Quick Start to get it running locally, then have your app connect to the development environment.</li>
-  </ol>
+  <p>You should develop against the beta release instead of this repo. Use this repo only if you want to develop against latest.</p>
 </details>
 
 <details>
-  <summary>About the commit history</summary>
-  <p>The original commits from the main repository are not preserved in this repository because they contain references to files that don't exist here. So, the Cardinal CI bot will create new commits that contain changes for only the files that are published to the self-hosted repository.</p>
-  <p>Unfortuntely, this process results in losing the original commit messages. The commits in this repository are also less granular, with each commit each containing everything from the last merge to main upstream.</p>
-  <p>I recognize the issues that this creates. If people actually want to use this repo then I'll try to improve it.</p>
+  <summary>Was this made with AI?</summary>
+  <p>No. This is, for better or for worse, all written by a human. Vive la révolution!</p>
 </details>
 
